{
    "publish_date": "2013-06-24T15:09:30.000Z", 
    "score": 0.00039799501482815715, 
    "video_length": "PT5M26S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "Imagine yourself standing on a beach,", 
            "dur": "2.361", 
            "start": "14.694"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "looking out over the ocean,", 
            "dur": "2.184", 
            "start": "17.055"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "waves crashing against the shore,", 
            "dur": "2.014", 
            "start": "19.239"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "blue as far as your eyes can see.", 
            "dur": "3.198", 
            "start": "21.253"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let it really sink in,", 
            "dur": "1.763", 
            "start": "24.451"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the sheer scope and size of it all.", 
            "dur": "2.696", 
            "start": "26.214"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now, ask yourself,", 
            "dur": "1.817", 
            "start": "28.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "&quot;How big is it?", 
            "dur": "1.974", 
            "start": "30.727"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "How big is the ocean?&quot;", 
            "dur": "2.983", 
            "start": "32.701"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "First thing, we need to understand", 
            "dur": "1.713", 
            "start": "35.684"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that there really is only one ocean,", 
            "dur": "1.958", 
            "start": "37.397"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "consisting of five component basins that we call", 
            "dur": "2.795", 
            "start": "39.355"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the Pacific,", 
            "dur": "1.084", 
            "start": "42.15"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the Atlantic,", 
            "dur": "0.584", 
            "start": "43.234"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the Indian,", 
            "dur": "0.667", 
            "start": "43.818"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the Arctic,", 
            "dur": "0.587", 
            "start": "44.485"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and the Southern.", 
            "dur": "1.582", 
            "start": "45.072"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Each of these five,", 
            "dur": "1.042", 
            "start": "46.654"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "while generally referred to as oceans", 
            "dur": "1.795", 
            "start": "47.696"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in and of themselves,", 
            "dur": "1.46", 
            "start": "49.491"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are really and truly a part of", 
            "dur": "1.585", 
            "start": "50.951"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "a single, massive body of water,", 
            "dur": "2.133", 
            "start": "52.536"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "one ocean,", 
            "dur": "1.062", 
            "start": "54.669"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which defines the very face of planet Earth.", 
            "dur": "2.811", 
            "start": "55.731"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The ocean covers roughly 71% of our planet&#39;s surface,", 
            "dur": "3.684", 
            "start": "58.542"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "some 360 million square kilometers,", 
            "dur": "3.171", 
            "start": "62.226"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "an area in excess of the size of 36 U.S.A.&#39;s.", 
            "dur": "4.151", 
            "start": "65.397"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s such a vast spread,", 
            "dur": "1.093", 
            "start": "69.548"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "when viewed from space,", 
            "dur": "1.377", 
            "start": "70.641"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the ocean is, by far, the dominant feature of our planet.", 
            "dur": "4.627", 
            "start": "72.018"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Speaking of space,", 
            "dur": "1.251", 
            "start": "76.645"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the ocean currently holds over 1.3 billion,", 
            "dur": "4.138", 
            "start": "77.896"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that&#39;s billion with a &quot;b&quot;,", 
            "dur": "1.702", 
            "start": "82.034"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "cubic kilometers of water.", 
            "dur": "1.915", 
            "start": "83.736"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Put another way,", 
            "dur": "1.046", 
            "start": "85.651"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that&#39;s enough water to immerse", 
            "dur": "1.574", 
            "start": "86.697"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the entire United States", 
            "dur": "1.96", 
            "start": "88.271"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "under a body of salt water", 
            "dur": "1.435", 
            "start": "90.231"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "over 132 kilometers tall,", 
            "dur": "2.864", 
            "start": "91.666"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "a height well beyond the reach of the highest clouds", 
            "dur": "2.971", 
            "start": "94.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and extending deep into the upper atmosphere.", 
            "dur": "3.508", 
            "start": "97.501"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "With all that volume,", 
            "dur": "1.21", 
            "start": "101.009"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the ocean represents 97%", 
            "dur": "2.759", 
            "start": "102.219"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of Earth&#39;s total water content.", 
            "dur": "2.735", 
            "start": "104.978"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "On top of all that,", 
            "dur": "1.596", 
            "start": "107.713"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the ocean contains upwards of 99%", 
            "dur": "3.057", 
            "start": "109.309"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of the world&#39;s biosphere,", 
            "dur": "1.864", 
            "start": "112.366"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that is, the spaces and places where life exists.", 
            "dur": "3.55", 
            "start": "114.23"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now let that sink in for a second.", 
            "dur": "2.123", 
            "start": "117.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The immediate world as we know it,", 
            "dur": "2.294", 
            "start": "119.903"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "indeed the totality of all the living space", 
            "dur": "2.994", 
            "start": "122.197"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "encompassed by the continents themselves,", 
            "dur": "2.136", 
            "start": "125.191"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "all of that represents only 1% of the biosphere.", 
            "dur": "4.464", 
            "start": "127.327"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "1%!", 
            "dur": "1.775", 
            "start": "131.791"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The ocean is everything else.", 
            "dur": "3.145", 
            "start": "133.566"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So, the ocean is physically massive.", 
            "dur": "3.713", 
            "start": "136.711"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s importance to life is practically unparalleled.", 
            "dur": "3.601", 
            "start": "140.424"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It also happens to hold", 
            "dur": "1.956", 
            "start": "144.025"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the greatest geological features of our planet.", 
            "dur": "3.314", 
            "start": "145.981"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Quickly, here are four of the most notable.", 
            "dur": "3.626", 
            "start": "152.048"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The ocean contains the world&#39;s largest mountain range,", 
            "dur": "2.807", 
            "start": "155.674"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the mid-ocean ridge.", 
            "dur": "1.629", 
            "start": "158.481"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "At roughly 65,000 kilometers long,", 
            "dur": "2.911", 
            "start": "160.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "this underwater range is some 10 times", 
            "dur": "2.993", 
            "start": "163.021"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "longer than the longest mountain chain", 
            "dur": "1.99", 
            "start": "166.014"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "found purely on dry land, the Andes.", 
            "dur": "2.506", 
            "start": "168.004"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Beneath the Denmark Strait exists", 
            "dur": "1.907", 
            "start": "170.51"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the world&#39;s largest waterfall.", 
            "dur": "2.639", 
            "start": "172.417"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This massive cataract carries roughly 116 times", 
            "dur": "4.422", 
            "start": "179.04"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "more water per second over its edge", 
            "dur": "2.906", 
            "start": "183.462"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "than the Congo River&#39;s Inga Falls,", 
            "dur": "1.972", 
            "start": "186.368"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the largest waterfall by volume on land.", 
            "dur": "3.42", 
            "start": "188.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The world&#39;s tallest mountain is actually found in the ocean,", 
            "dur": "2.795", 
            "start": "191.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "hiding in plain sight.", 
            "dur": "1.71", 
            "start": "194.555"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "While 4200 meters of Hawaii&#39;s Mauna Kea", 
            "dur": "2.419", 
            "start": "196.265"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "sit above sea level,", 
            "dur": "1.959", 
            "start": "198.684"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "its sides plummet beneath the waves", 
            "dur": "2.07", 
            "start": "200.643"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "for another 5800 meters.", 
            "dur": "2.352", 
            "start": "202.713"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "From its snow-covered top", 
            "dur": "1.418", 
            "start": "205.065"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to it&#39;s silt-covered bottom, then,", 
            "dur": "2.171", 
            "start": "206.483"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "this Hawaiian mountain is roughly 10,000 meters in height,", 
            "dur": "3.175", 
            "start": "208.654"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "dwarfing tiny Everest&#39;s paltry peak", 
            "dur": "2.293", 
            "start": "211.829"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by well over a kilometer.", 
            "dur": "1.828", 
            "start": "214.122"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Then, since we&#39;re picking on poor Everest,", 
            "dur": "2.155", 
            "start": "215.95"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "let&#39;s consider the world&#39;s deepest canyon,", 
            "dur": "2.726", 
            "start": "218.105"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the Challenger Deep,", 
            "dur": "1.612", 
            "start": "220.831"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "existing 11 kilometers below the ocean&#39;s surface,", 
            "dur": "2.935", 
            "start": "222.443"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "some six times deeper than the Grand Canyon.", 
            "dur": "2.451", 
            "start": "225.378"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s deep enough to sink Mount Everest into", 
            "dur": "2.641", 
            "start": "227.829"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and still have over 2.1 kilometers of water", 
            "dur": "3.169", 
            "start": "230.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "sitting atop its newly submerged peak.", 
            "dur": "2.407", 
            "start": "233.639"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Put another way, the depth of the Challenger Deep", 
            "dur": "2.538", 
            "start": "236.046"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is roughly the same height", 
            "dur": "1.585", 
            "start": "238.584"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that commercial airliners travel.", 
            "dur": "2.086", 
            "start": "240.169"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So, pretty much however you choose to slice it,", 
            "dur": "2.646", 
            "start": "242.255"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the ocean is capital B", 
            "dur": "2.041", 
            "start": "244.901"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "capital I,", 
            "dur": "0.819", 
            "start": "246.942"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "capital G,", 
            "dur": "1.131", 
            "start": "247.761"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BIG!", 
            "dur": "1.157", 
            "start": "248.892"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It defines our planet,", 
            "dur": "1.941", 
            "start": "250.049"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "home to the greatest geological features,", 
            "dur": "2.486", 
            "start": "251.99"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "comprises the largest living space,", 
            "dur": "2.419", 
            "start": "254.476"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and accordingly, is home to the greatest numbers", 
            "dur": "2.627", 
            "start": "256.895"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and forms of life on Earth.", 
            "dur": "2.384", 
            "start": "259.522"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It is practically incomprehensible in scope.", 
            "dur": "3.827", 
            "start": "261.906"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But it is not so big,", 
            "dur": "2.919", 
            "start": "265.733"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so vast,", 
            "dur": "1.229", 
            "start": "268.652"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "so extraordinary", 
            "dur": "1.361", 
            "start": "269.881"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as to be untouchable.", 
            "dur": "2.086", 
            "start": "271.242"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, with roughly 50% of the world&#39;s population", 
            "dur": "3.745", 
            "start": "273.328"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "living within 100 kilometers of the coastline", 
            "dur": "2.649", 
            "start": "277.073"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and with most of the remainder", 
            "dur": "1.998", 
            "start": "279.722"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "living close enough to lakes, rivers, or swamps,", 
            "dur": "2.786", 
            "start": "281.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "all of which ultimately lead to the ocean,", 
            "dur": "2.481", 
            "start": "284.506"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "virtually every single person on the planet", 
            "dur": "2.585", 
            "start": "286.987"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "has the opportunity to influence the general health", 
            "dur": "3.422", 
            "start": "289.572"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and nature of the world ocean.", 
            "dur": "2.55", 
            "start": "292.994"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Evidence of human influence is seen", 
            "dur": "1.68", 
            "start": "295.544"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "in every part of the ocean,", 
            "dur": "1.993", 
            "start": "297.224"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "no matter how deep,", 
            "dur": "1.263", 
            "start": "299.217"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "no matter how distant.", 
            "dur": "1.9", 
            "start": "300.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The ocean defines our planet,", 
            "dur": "2.893", 
            "start": "302.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but, in a very real sense,", 
            "dur": "2.142", 
            "start": "305.273"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "we define the ocean.", 
            "dur": "2.206", 
            "start": "307.415"
        }
    ], 
